Several people, her friends included, blamed her for writing, and this past year, once she’d began publication on her stories, most of these problems were placed back at her feet once again.

“One guy in front of the school told me I can be so lazy as to write down boring, unnecessary stories instead of learning things that matter. Another person from uni told me that literary fiction has nothing to offer the world, and that person said it to me during a collage subject about how to write a short story!! That really pissed me off.”

Since We’re All Going to Die out soon, I’ve been wary of asking Amina to even take another step into the world of digital media. Recently, I asked her what her favorite social media is, and surprisingly, Twitter. “This kind of writing culture where people share their opinions online is one of the few help to me in times of doubt about my writing future. Where else am I going to go but to someone who shares this belief in good writing?”

Did I Need to Write This? Asks Rio Mangini, a seventeen-year-old freshman at Lyman Hall high school
